00:14:02,631 --> 00:14:05,152
that best suit your online style and audience,

227
00:14:05,412 --> 00:14:06,212
and set up accounts.

228
00:14:06,812 --> 00:14:09,233
I'll go into more detail later about how to decide that.

229
00:14:09,953 --> 00:14:12,554
Then you want to set up a website and a press kit for your game.

230
00:14:12,994 --> 00:14:16,175
The website should contain information and links to everything.

231
00:14:16,576 --> 00:14:21,577
You want one central hub where people can go to get all the information they need about your game.

232
00:14:22,177 --> 00:14:30,320
What it is, a trailer for the game, how to contact you, how to follow the game, when it's releasing, what platforms it's coming out on, etc.

233
00:14:31,688 --> 00:14:33,890
You can Google Indie Video Games Press Kit,

234
00:14:34,350 --> 00:14:36,751
and you'll get a template that's super easy to use.

235
00:14:37,431 --> 00:14:39,952
And this is really vital to provide information to the press.

236
00:14:40,413 --> 00:14:42,294
You don't ever want to be in a situation

237
00:14:42,334 --> 00:14:44,555
where a member of the press wants to cover your game,

238
00:14:44,855 --> 00:14:46,616
but doesn't because they don't have access

239
00:14:46,636 --> 00:14:48,336
to important materials about your game.

240
00:14:48,577 --> 00:14:50,277
That's why you want to make sure you have a press kit.

241
00:14:52,258 --> 00:14:53,559
And then set up your Steam page.

242
00:14:55,280 --> 00:14:59,223
Once you start building up followers, you need somewhere to direct them to go wishlist your game.

243
00:14:59,963 --> 00:15:01,845
I'll go more into setting up the Steam page later.

244
00:15:01,865 --> 00:15:06,348
And then set up a Discord if you have the capacity to manage it.

245
00:15:06,848 --> 00:15:11,331
A Discord is not necessary, but it can be very important to keep your community in one

246
00:15:11,391 --> 00:15:16,235
place to be able to interact with your fans directly and provide dev updates in a chill way.

247
00:15:17,332 --> 00:15:18,332
and put up a demo.

248
00:15:18,332 --> 00:15:21,294
This is a great way to get people interested in your game.

249
00:15:21,332 --> 00:15:25,294
Don't do this until you're ready, of course, and be willing to hear and respond to feedback.

250
00:15:25,894 --> 00:15:28,797
But there are plenty of SteamFests that you can put a demo up for,

251
00:15:28,894 --> 00:15:33,797
or you can put a demo of your game up on itch.io to make sure that you can send people to a place

252
00:15:33,797 --> 00:15:36,797
where they can play your game and get a better sense of what it's like.

253
00:15:37,297 --> 00:15:40,279
A lot of people will discover demos of games just by scrolling through itch.

254
00:15:40,297 --> 00:15:44,279
A lot of content creators do that as well, so it's worth looking into.

255
00:15:48,261 --> 00:15:52,225
Now I'm going to go into the various social media platforms you can use to promote your game.

256
00:15:52,846 --> 00:15:54,788
To start, let's talk about Twitter.

257
00:15:55,568 --> 00:16:00,233
I used to be a very strong proponent of using Twitter to engage with people and market your

258
00:16:00,253 --> 00:16:04,097
game, but in the past two years, the site has fallen pretty far from grace.

259
00:16:04,217 --> 00:16:09,462
So while it's still important for networking, it's not the most vital platform for marketing.

260
00:16:10,363 --> 00:16:12,363
If you decide to start a Twitter,

261
00:16:12,363 --> 00:16:17,407
you'll need to decide if you want a studio Twitter, a game Twitter, and or a personal Twitter.

262
00:16:17,427 --> 00:16:23,311
A personal Twitter is good for showing the person behind the game. This goes back to the people follow people tip.

263
00:16:23,892 --> 00:16:28,094
But it can also be harder to separate your personal musings from important stuff about the game.

264
00:16:28,455 --> 00:16:31,957
So if you're the kind of person that likes to tweet every thought that pops into your head,

265
00:16:32,938 --> 00:16:35,159
it's better for you to set up a separate account for your game.

266
00:16:36,942 --> 00:16:40,206
If you're working with a group of people, you should either have a studio Twitter or

267
00:16:40,226 --> 00:16:43,289
a game Twitter, so fans can follow one account to get updates.

268
00:16:43,730 --> 00:16:47,854
It's hard to cultivate a community if your updates are scattered across multiple different

269
00:16:47,874 --> 00:16:48,855
people's Twitter accounts.

270
00:16:49,884 --> 00:16:51,145
Remember, people follow people.

271
00:16:51,245 --> 00:16:56,507
So even if you're running a studio game Twitter, a studio or a game Twitter, followers will

272
00:16:56,567 --> 00:16:59,648
still engage more when they know they're engaging with a real person.

273
00:17:00,249 --> 00:17:03,570
Social media can feel disingenuous, especially if you're not used to it.

274
00:17:04,070 --> 00:17:06,211
But try to be fun, kind, and engaging.

275
00:17:06,631 --> 00:17:08,952
You don't need to be corporate or stilted.

276
00:17:09,113 --> 00:17:11,474
You don't need to speak in marketing speak all the time.

277
00:17:11,814 --> 00:17:12,914
You're making a video game.

278
00:17:13,354 --> 00:17:14,195
That's a cool thing.

279
00:17:14,255 --> 00:17:15,175
That's a fun thing.

280
00:17:15,815 --> 00:17:19,077
And you want tweets that people will enjoy reading and want to interact with.

281
00:17:20,017 --> 00:17:22,657
And feel free to post about more than just your game.

282
00:17:23,197 --> 00:17:26,198
You can post random thoughts, support your fellow indie devs,

283
00:17:26,538 --> 00:17:30,019
you can post, you know, a fun meme that's relevant to the game that you're making,

284
00:17:30,519 --> 00:17:33,319
anything that'll get people to engage with the content that you're making.

285
00:17:34,500 --> 00:17:36,880
And importantly, don't overload your tweets with hashtags.

286
00:17:37,300 --> 00:17:39,181
They're not the discovery tool that you think they are,

287
00:17:39,361 --> 00:17:41,281
and they're really only good for specific things,

288
00:17:41,361 --> 00:17:44,702
like hashtag Screenshot Saturday, or Twitter campaigns,

289
00:17:44,902 --> 00:17:46,942
or connecting directly with a community.

290
00:17:49,066 --> 00:17:52,954
So here are a few examples of tweets from indie devs that have done really well. The

291
00:17:52,994 --> 00:17:57,584
first is from my friend who's making a game called Olliefrog Toad Skater. Um, you'll notice

292
00:17:57,665 --> 00:17:59,228
a few things about this tweet.

293
00:18:00,145 --> 00:18:03,888
It's not a lot of text, so people's eyes won't glaze over trying to read it.

294
00:18:04,448 --> 00:18:08,610
It uses emoji to illustrate what the text is saying, which gives it a little bit of flair.

295
00:18:09,271 --> 00:18:14,153
And it uses just one hashtag, the game dev hashtag, which can surface it in game dev

296
00:18:14,213 --> 00:18:16,114
communities without overloading the tweet.

297
00:18:16,655 --> 00:18:19,276
It also includes a very cool video that shows off the tweet.

298
00:18:19,296 --> 00:18:21,397
And this is the most important part, the visual.

299
00:18:22,398 --> 00:18:24,199
The video shows off what the text says.

300
00:18:24,659 --> 00:18:27,001
It gets right into the action, and it stays in the action.

301
00:18:27,381 --> 00:18:29,482
And it shows how vibrant and fun the world is.

302
00:18:31,827 --> 00:18:36,349
Here's another example of an indie game tweet that appeals a little bit more to the development side of Twitter.

303
00:18:36,809 --> 00:18:40,711
This is from the developer of the game Sail Forth, which I did some marketing and production work on.

304
00:18:41,451 --> 00:18:45,833
Note that the text of the tweet isn't too technical or too much getting into the weeds.

305
00:18:46,528 --> 00:18:49,990
This will catch the eye of people who know what the developer is talking about,

306
00:18:50,510 --> 00:18:52,631
who can then read the rest of this Twitter thread,

307
00:18:52,691 --> 00:18:56,232
because this was a thread going into the details of development.

308
00:18:56,773 --> 00:18:59,133
But for people who aren't on the technical side of development,

309
00:18:59,234 --> 00:19:00,814
for fans of games, for example,

310
00:19:01,314 --> 00:19:04,216
the video does a good job visually representing what he's saying

311
00:19:05,036 --> 00:19:06,476
in a way that still makes sense.

312
00:19:07,197 --> 00:19:10,698
Gamers who don't know much about development can still appreciate this video,

313
00:19:11,078 --> 00:19:14,380
and getting a behind-the-scenes glimpse makes them more excited to play the game,

314
00:19:14,580 --> 00:19:16,160
to see how it plays out in real time.

315
00:19:19,986 --> 00:19:24,431
And bolstered by the need to stay entertained and engaged throughout the pandemic, TikTok

316
00:19:24,451 --> 00:19:29,215
has emerged as the top runner for best social media to promo your game on, if you can hit

317
00:19:29,235 --> 00:19:30,056
the algorithm right.

318
00:19:31,017 --> 00:19:35,621
Now this advice may very soon become irrelevant if TikTok gets banned in the US, but for now,

319
00:19:35,862 --> 00:19:36,783
let's act like it won't.

320
00:19:38,701 --> 00:19:44,669
I'm not a TikTok expert, and there are a few other talks here at GDC that will have more information than I do

321
00:19:44,701 --> 00:19:46,669
about how best to create content for TikTok specifically.

322
00:19:47,290 --> 00:19:49,712
But much of the same rules as Twitter apply here.

323
00:19:50,193 --> 00:19:53,216
Don't be too corporate, show your personality, have fun with it.

324
00:19:53,937 --> 00:19:59,280
Trends are important on TikTok, so make sure you take some time to understand the app before posting to it.

325
00:19:59,681 --> 00:20:02,082
Learn how to use trending sounds and hashtags.

326
00:20:02,803 --> 00:20:07,446
TikTok is hard to parse, and you will likely fail quite a bit before getting a hit TikTok,

327
00:20:07,546 --> 00:20:12,710
but I really do think it's the biggest driver of interests and wishlists of all the social media platforms.

328
00:20:13,610 --> 00:20:15,411
It's all about viral content.

329
00:20:15,991 --> 00:20:18,412
It's a bit harder to cultivate a community through TikTok,

330
00:20:18,472 --> 00:20:20,273
but it's a great way to reach the masses.

331
00:20:20,593 --> 00:20:24,435
Games that go viral on TikTok often get noticed by journalists and streamers,

332
00:20:24,835 --> 00:20:27,896
and all it takes is one popular video to get a lot of attention.

333
00:20:30,237 --> 00:20:33,938
Here are a few indie game TikTok accounts that have been wildly successful.

334
00:20:34,498 --> 00:20:37,860
I highly recommend you check them out to see what hits and what doesn't.

335
00:20:39,010 --> 00:20:43,112
One More Multiverse is a great example of an account that uses being personable as a

336
00:20:43,152 --> 00:20:44,112
way to explain their game.

337
00:20:44,172 --> 00:20:48,194
A lot of times one of the developers will be in the video themselves showing their face.

338
00:20:49,955 --> 00:20:54,617
The game Mail Time has found a lot of success by the creator showing her development process

339
00:20:54,657 --> 00:20:57,378
and posting clips of funny bugs that are going on in her game.

340
00:20:58,959 --> 00:21:02,720
Landfall Games is a bigger studio, but they've done a great job getting a huge following

341
00:21:02,760 --> 00:21:06,602
on TikTok because they have a lot of silly games and they like to post little clips from that.

342
00:21:08,329 --> 00:21:10,730
Inky Fox is the solo dev of the game Omno.

343
00:21:11,170 --> 00:21:12,951
And if you can see, they're tiny numbers,

344
00:21:13,011 --> 00:21:14,791
but you can see those first videos there all

345
00:21:14,831 --> 00:21:17,792
have millions of views, which contributed

346
00:21:17,852 --> 00:21:19,052
to the success of that game.

347
00:21:19,473 --> 00:21:22,473
He posted a lot about what it's like being a solo dev, what

348
00:21:22,493 --> 00:21:24,274
it's like developing this game, and that

349
00:21:24,314 --> 00:21:25,434
got him a lot of followers.

350
00:21:27,875 --> 00:21:30,076
And then this game from one of the creators of the game Tiny

351
00:21:30,136 --> 00:21:32,437
Glade, you can see, again, that first video there

352
00:21:32,457 --> 00:21:34,437
has almost 10 million views on TikTok.

353
00:21:35,329 --> 00:21:40,571
Now, Anastasia Opara recently posted a great Twitter thread breaking down the TikTok strategy,

354
00:21:40,831 --> 00:21:43,372
so definitely check that out if that's something you're interested in.

355
00:21:43,912 --> 00:21:47,733
And often the people running these accounts will post blog posts or Twitter threads going

356
00:21:47,773 --> 00:21:48,674
through their process.

357
00:21:49,134 --> 00:21:52,835
There are plenty more examples out there, so do a little bit of research and chat with

358
00:21:52,855 --> 00:21:57,277
your friends and other people you know who are using TikTok to see what approach is best for you.

359
00:22:01,044 --> 00:22:06,829
Like I said earlier, Discord can be a really good place to build a community as long as you have the energy and time to take care of it.

360
00:22:07,609 --> 00:22:09,951
A good Discord community can make an indie game.

361
00:22:10,332 --> 00:22:13,974
But remember, your community is a reflection of your game and you.

362
00:22:14,175 --> 00:22:17,377
So be sure to set rules and moderate to cultivate your community.

363
00:22:18,058 --> 00:22:22,701
Make sure you use your Discord as more than a place to just throw devlogs in and leave it alone.

364
00:22:23,242 --> 00:22:27,765
Chat with your fans, talk about the other games that you're playing, other hobbies that you have,

365
00:22:28,165 --> 00:22:29,386
show off your art to each other.

366
00:22:30,527 --> 00:22:34,568
If you're comfortable with it, you can set up monthly voice calls or dev streams to chat

367
00:22:34,648 --> 00:22:36,068
live with the people in your Discord.

368
00:22:36,969 --> 00:22:39,229
It's good to give perks to people in your Discord.

369
00:22:39,429 --> 00:22:44,010
These are the true fans of you and your game, and you want them to feel special and appreciated.

370
00:22:44,590 --> 00:22:49,111
You can do game key giveaways, you can give them behind-the-scenes info, you can do polls

371
00:22:49,171 --> 00:22:51,652
to let your community make small decisions about your game.

372
00:22:52,492 --> 00:22:56,453
You can even encourage them to do fan art of your game and chat with them about the

373
00:22:56,473 --> 00:22:57,513
process of development.

374
00:22:59,839 --> 00:23:04,481
Okay, yes, Steam is not technically a social media platform, but it is important to use

375
00:23:04,641 --> 00:23:06,502
if you're planning to release your game on Steam.

376
00:23:07,282 --> 00:23:12,204
You'll want to set up your Steam page as soon as possible, unless you're seeking a publisher,

377
00:23:12,324 --> 00:23:16,845
but even still, most smaller publishers are going to want to see a game on Steam already

378
00:23:16,925 --> 00:23:19,846
so that they can see the interest and wish list that you have.

379
00:23:20,927 --> 00:23:26,229
You want to set up your Steam page as soon as you have good art to use for the capsules and the screenshots.

380
00:23:26,849 --> 00:23:30,311
You can change the art as many times as you want, so don't worry if it's not final.

381
00:23:32,071 --> 00:23:35,313
Use that message that we came up with earlier as your short description,

382
00:23:35,693 --> 00:23:38,954
and be sure to include the bullet points in the long description of the game.

383
00:23:39,845 --> 00:23:44,108
Remember that wishlists convert anywhere from 10 to 30% to sales in the first year.

384
00:23:44,709 --> 00:23:48,531
So make sure you're accumulating the number of wishlists you want before launch.

385
00:23:48,812 --> 00:23:52,654
If you're the one setting your launch release date and you don't have the number of wishlists

386
00:23:52,674 --> 00:23:56,417
that you really want to have in order to make the sales you want, you can just delay your

387
00:23:56,437 --> 00:23:58,518
game a little bit to do a little bit more marketing.

388
00:23:59,880 --> 00:24:04,143
And use the Steam announcements feature to tell followers about your development process.

389
00:24:04,643 --> 00:24:08,845
Any Steam events your game is in, when a new demo is up, anything like that.

390
00:24:09,466 --> 00:24:13,468
Short of the $100 you have to pay to put a game on Steam, it's free marketing.

391
00:24:14,168 --> 00:24:18,651
The discussion section of your community page on Steam is a great place to cultivate your community.

392
00:24:18,951 --> 00:24:22,593
Players will ask questions and leave feedback there, and those are going to be the most

393
00:24:22,653 --> 00:24:24,674
excited and hardcore players for your game.

394
00:24:25,234 --> 00:24:27,415
Be responsive, and they'll spread the word for you.

395
00:24:29,064 --> 00:24:33,528
Speaking of people spreading the word for you, this is also not technically a social

396
00:24:33,568 --> 00:24:37,272
media platform, but word-of-mouth marketing cannot be underestimated.

397
00:24:37,792 --> 00:24:41,976
There's going to be a portion of your players who aren't chronically online, who don't have

398
00:24:42,016 --> 00:24:45,940
Twitter accounts or TikToks, and who don't check the Steam discovery queue every week

399
00:24:45,980 --> 00:24:47,582
to find games that they'd like to play.

400
00:24:48,442 --> 00:24:51,524
Word-of-mouth marketing is nearly impossible to quantify,

401
00:24:51,784 --> 00:24:54,866
but it's important to remember that no one will talk about your game

402
00:24:54,986 --> 00:24:57,107
unless you're also talking about your game.

403
00:24:57,887 --> 00:25:00,889
If there are people you regularly hang out with or interact with

404
00:25:00,969 --> 00:25:03,590
that don't know you're making a game, that needs to change.

405
00:25:04,150 --> 00:25:05,391
You don't need to be annoying about it,

406
00:25:05,711 --> 00:25:09,213
but keep your friends updated on what you're doing and what you're working on.

407
00:25:09,553 --> 00:25:12,195
Making a game is cool. Your friends want to support you.

408
00:25:13,397 --> 00:25:15,219
Even strangers will support you if you're friendly.

409
00:25:15,999 --> 00:25:19,362
If you're taking regular horseback riding lessons, it would be a good idea to slip in

410
00:25:19,482 --> 00:25:22,285
a, hey, did you know I'm working on a video game about horses?

411
00:25:23,125 --> 00:25:25,327
And you'll get other people interested in what you're working on.

412
00:25:26,008 --> 00:25:27,249
I'll give you a real life example.

413
00:25:27,749 --> 00:25:31,953
Recently I had stopped by a smoked salmon shop in Seattle, where I'm from, to buy a

414
00:25:31,993 --> 00:25:33,254
gift for my dad for the holidays.

415
00:25:33,914 --> 00:25:37,876
I asked the cashier for some recommendations, and then we started chatting about when I

416
00:25:37,916 --> 00:25:39,677
had moved to Seattle and what I was doing.

417
00:25:40,317 --> 00:25:43,038
Started talking to him about my job and the games that I had worked on.

418
00:25:43,458 --> 00:25:46,479
And now he's writing down the titles of the games that I'm working on.

419
00:25:46,539 --> 00:25:50,261
He's like, this is so cool, I'm really interested in this game, I'm going to go home and play it.

420
00:25:50,741 --> 00:25:54,123
All because I just started up a small conversation with a person in a shop.

421
00:25:54,783 --> 00:25:58,444
And that also means that other people in that shop were hearing me talk about the game that

422
00:25:58,464 --> 00:25:59,025
I'm working on.

423
00:25:59,045 --> 00:26:00,405
And they may also be interested in it.

424
00:26:03,632 --> 00:26:08,274
You should also make sure to have some sort of take home item about your game, especially

425
00:26:08,454 --> 00:26:09,995
if you're going to a conference like this one.

426
00:26:10,655 --> 00:26:14,396
This can be business cards or postcards with info about where to find your game.

427
00:26:15,097 --> 00:26:18,998
And a shout out to the developers I met yesterday who pulled out a Steam deck with a build of

428
00:26:19,038 --> 00:26:19,739
their game on it.

429
00:26:19,819 --> 00:26:21,899
That was a super cool way to see a game in action.

430
00:26:23,460 --> 00:26:27,343
You could also consider making a cool t-shirt with your game's title and imagery on it,

431
00:26:27,483 --> 00:26:31,666
or some sort of fun phrase that'll get people approaching you and asking you about it.

432
00:26:32,267 --> 00:26:34,929
You could make stickers to hand out to people who seem interested.

433
00:26:35,369 --> 00:26:39,572
Make the stickers cool enough to be attractive to people who are into more than just your game,

434
00:26:39,612 --> 00:26:44,095
but also include the game's title or aesthetic so that people remember what it is about.

435
00:26:45,777 --> 00:26:49,179
But also be kind to the environment and don't put stickers all over everything everywhere.

436
00:26:51,527 --> 00:26:56,128
There are a lot of other platforms you can use to build a following, and each has its pros and cons.

437
00:26:56,728 --> 00:26:58,389
And here's a quick rundown of a few more.

438
00:26:58,869 --> 00:27:03,771
Kickstarter is a lot of work, but it does give you a built-in following and funding.

439
00:27:04,231 --> 00:27:08,793
It's up to you to decide if you're willing to sink the time and energy into running a Kickstarter.

440
00:27:09,553 --> 00:27:11,133
Reddit is like the Wild West.

441
00:27:11,293 --> 00:27:15,855
I've seen indie games go viral on there successfully, but it seems to be mostly dumb luck.

442
00:27:16,635 --> 00:27:21,578
If you're already an avid Reddit user, I'd recommend posting info about your games in the relevant subreddits,

443
00:27:21,778 --> 00:27:24,219
but if you're not, I wouldn't say it's worth the time.

444
00:27:24,339 --> 00:27:27,020
There can be a lot of specific rules to each of the subreddits,

445
00:27:27,580 --> 00:27:32,643
